PHASE 2 — SQL (This is where professionals separate)

Use PostgreSQL / MySQL / SQLite.

Step-by-step SQL Plan

1️⃣ Load Data

SQL
COPY purchase_orders FROM 'purchase_orders.csv' CSV HEADER;

2️⃣ Core KPIs (Examples)

Delay Flag

SQL
CASE 
  WHEN actual_delivery > expected_delivery THEN 1 
  ELSE 0 
END AS is_delayed

Vendor Delay %

SQL
SELECT vendor_id,
       COUNT(*) AS total_orders,
       SUM(is_delayed) * 100.0 / COUNT(*) AS delay_pct
FROM purchase_orders
GROUP BY vendor_id;

Quarter-wise Trend

SQL
DATE_TRUNC('quarter', order_date)

You are NOT memorizing SQL — you’re answering questions.

How SQLite differs from MySQL / PostgreSQL

MySQL / PostgreSQL (server-based)

  • You must:

    • start a server

    • create database explicitly

    • manage users/passwords

SQLite (file-based)

  • Database = just a file

  • No server

  • No manual “CREATE DATABASE” step

Think of it like this:

Plain text
SQLite DB = Excel file, but with SQL power

When Python opens the file path, SQLite creates the file if missing.

import pandas as pd
import sqlite3

# Load data
df = pd.read_csv("../data/DataCoSupplyChainDataset.csv", encoding="latin1")

# Convert dates (mixed format safe)
df["order date (DateOrders)"] = pd.to_datetime(
    df["order date (DateOrders)"],
    format="mixed",
    dayfirst=True
)

df["shipping date (DateOrders)"] = pd.to_datetime(
    df["shipping date (DateOrders)"],
    format="mixed",
    dayfirst=True
)

# Delay logic
df["delay_days"] = (
    df["Days for shipping (real)"] -
    df["Days for shipment (scheduled)"]
)

df["is_delayed"] = (df["delay_days"] > 0).astype(int)

# Select only fact columns
cols = [
    "Order Id",
    "order date (DateOrders)",
    "shipping date (DateOrders)",
    "Days for shipping (real)",
    "Days for shipment (scheduled)",
    "delay_days",
    "is_delayed",
    "Late_delivery_risk",
    "Sales",
    "Order Item Total",
    "Order Profit Per Order",
    "Product Card Id",
    "Product Name",
    "Category Name",
    "Department Name",
    "Order Country",
    "Order Region",
    "Shipping Mode"
]

orders_fact = df[cols]

# Create / connect SQLite DB (auto-created)
conn = sqlite3.connect("../sql/supply_chain.db")

# Load into SQL
orders_fact.to_sql(
    name="orders_fact",
    con=conn,
    if_exists="replace",
    index=False
)

conn.close()

Python
import sqlite3
import pandas as pd

conn = sqlite3.connect("../sql/supply_chain.db")

query = """
SELECT
    Order Region,
    Shipping Mode,
    COUNT(*) AS total_orders,
    SUM(is_delayed) AS delayed_orders,
    ROUND(100.0 * SUM(is_delayed) / COUNT(*), 2) AS delay_percentage
FROM orders_fact
GROUP BY Order Region, Shipping Mode
ORDER BY delay_percentage DESC;
"""

delay_kpi = pd.read_sql(query, conn)
conn.close()

query = """
SELECT
    "Category Name" AS category,
    "Shipping Mode" AS shipping_mode,
    COUNT(*) AS total_orders,
    SUM(is_delayed) AS delayed_orders,
    ROUND(100.0 * SUM(is_delayed) / COUNT(*), 2) AS delay_percentage
FROM orders_fact
WHERE "Shipping Mode" != 'First Class'
GROUP BY category, shipping_mode
HAVING COUNT(*) > 200
ORDER BY delay_percentage DESC;
"""

What’s wrong (clear and blunt)

You’re seeing:

  • Total Orders: 180.519K ✅ (correct)

  • Delayed Orders: 103K ✅ (reasonable)

  • Sum of Delay %: 10340.0K% ❌❌❌

That Delay % card is wrong by definition.

Why?

Because Power BI is summing a percentage column row by row.

Percentages should NEVER be summed.

This is a classic rookie error — and interviewers will catch it.

What Delay % SHOULD be

Delay % must be calculated as:

\text{Delay %} = \frac{\text{Total Delayed Orders}}{\text{Total Orders}}

Not row-wise.
Not summed.
Not averaged blindly.

The FIX (do this exactly)

STEP 1 — Delete the wrong Delay % card

  • Select the card showing Sum of Delay %

  • Press Delete

We will NOT reuse that field.

STEP 2 — Create a proper DAX measure

In Modeling → New measure, paste this:

DAX
Delay % =
DIVIDE(
    SUM(orders_fact_final[is_delayed]),
    COUNT(orders_fact_final[Order Id]),
    0
)

Why this is correct:

  • SUM(is_delayed) → total delayed orders

  • COUNT(Order Id) → total orders

  • DIVIDE → safe division (no errors)

STEP 3 — Format the measure

  • Select the Delay % measure

  • Format → Percentage

  • Decimal places → 1

Expected value will be around 57%–60% (based on your data).
